    purduePA09r2¶

    Results | Participants | Proceedings | Input | Summary | Appendix

    • Run ID: purduePA09r2
    • Participant: Purdue_Si
    • Track: Chemical
    • Year: 2009
    • Submission: 9/6/2009
    • Type: automatic
    • Task: priorart_sm
    • MD5: 35cf985046f92ffa13d91a87d607e2d1
    • Run description: To construct the queries from patent files, we used all title words, and selected sets of terms from the claims, abstract and description fields of query patents (top 30 terms with respect to TF-IDF scores are chosen for each). From those terms, chemical entities are extracted and synonyms for the identified chemical entities are also included from PubChem. Then structured queries are formed to do retrieval over different fields of documents with different weights. Then some of the retrieved documents are filtered out from the ranked list because of date constraints (if their minimum priority date is after the maximum priority date of the query file). If priority dates don't exist, we use publication date as the corresponding dates. Last but not the least, IPC similarities between query patent and its retrieved patents are exploited to rerank the retrieved documents.

    UIowaS09PA1¶

    Results | Participants | Proceedings | Input | Summary (full) | Summary (small) | Appendix

    • Run ID: UIowaS09PA1
    • Participant: IowaS
    • Track: Chemical
    • Year: 2009
    • Submission: 9/4/2009
    • Type: automatic
    • Task: priorart
    • MD5: 93a8e5d3da6513d6d13755c9357f359e
    • Run description: We produced 2 separate indexes using Lucene: one using the claims and title information only; the other using other information in the patent including the description, abstract, and classification. We used a specific technique to "un-nest" the claims so they would each be independent documents for evaluation. After limiting the available matching patents using the priority date as a threshold, we merged these two indexes using a weighted ratio and obtained a ranked list of resultant patent documents. These patents were then unduplicated, taking the lowest ranked value of a candidate patent.
